<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-406-486  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 406 486.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  May 1990 v15 n5 p262(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Around the world in text displays. (implementing foreign-languagecharacter sets on microcomputers)(includes related article onforeign-language Macintosh system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, Ben.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Developing microcomputer systems that recognize foreign-languagecharacter sets is a major challenge for system designers.andP;  Today'sfaster processors, low-cost memory, and high resolution displaysallow the creation of Cyrillic, Hebrew, Greek, Arabic, Chinese,and Japanese alphabets in computer operating systems.andP;  Characterson IBM PC compatibles and computer terminals are stored as arraysof bits within character cells; creating diacritical marks is aproblem because the entire character cell is rewritten when thesystem copies a character from memory to the screen, forcingdefinition of separate characters for each diacritic and basecharacter combination.andP;  David Packard Jr's Ibycus special-purposecomputer is a word processor and text searching machine for Latin,Greek, Hebrew, and Coptic.andP;  Arabic writing is complex because ithas multiple cases and use s stretch character forms.andP;  PrintingArabic requires a laser or 24-pin dot-matrix printer.andP;  Chinese andJapanese characters are pictographic and ideographic rather thanphonetic.andP;  The entire Chinese language includes 8,000commonly-used characters and more than 40,000 characters in all.andO;Japanese writing uses three different kinds of writing: kanji, thetraditional, formal or writing; katakana, a phonetic alphabet usedto spell foreign words; and the informal, abbreviated hiragana.andO;Users usually enter Japanese characters phonetically by spellingout Anglicized versions, an unintuitive process for Japanese.andO;Affordable solutions now exist for the most widely used non-Romanalphabets.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Systems SoftwareForeign LanguagesLanguage TranslationMicrocomputersAlphabetsCharacter SetsNon-Roman Alphabets.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   How characters are formed. (chart)Arabic: a moving display. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>